      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;introduction-to-solid-state-physics&#34;&gt;Introduction to Solid State Physics&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Solid-state physics is the study of rigid matter, or solids, through methods such as quantum mechanics, crystallography, electromagnetism, and metallurgy. It is the largest branch of condensed matter physics. Solid-state physics studies how the large-scale properties of solid materials result from their atomic-scale properties. Thus, solid-state physics forms a theoretical basis of materials science. It also has direct applications, for example in the technology of transistors and semiconductors.&lt;/p&gt;
